properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: High temperatures and humidity are expected over much of southern and western Nova Scotia today. Time span: continuing into this evening. Maximum daytime temperatures: near 29 degrees Celsius, except cooler along parts of the coast. Locations: southern and western Nova Scotia. Remarks: Maximum temperatures today will once again reach warning criteria over southern and western portions of the province. Although humidex values will be in the low 30s on Thursday, maximum temperatures are expected to reach only the mid 20s, and this warning is likely to be ended this evening in these areas. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. Heat warnings are issued when very high temperature or humidity conditions are expected to pose an elevated risk of heat illnesses, such as heat stroke or heat exhaustion. Information is provided on the Nova Scotia Department of Health and Wellness website at https://novascotia.ca/heat-related-illness/. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Temperatures reaching 32 degrees Celsius combined with overnight lows near 16 degrees Celsius are expected for the next 2 days. A hot air mass will spread across southern Saskatchewan this week, sending temperatures into the low 30s with overnight lows in the mid-teens. The heat will be concentrated over the southwest corner of the province today, but will spread eastwards with increasing humidity through the week. In the southwest, slightly cooler temperatures will bring an end to the warning level conditions for Friday. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. Watch for the effects of heat illness: swelling, rash, cramps, fainting, heat exhaustion, heat stroke and the worsening of some health conditions. Please call HealthLine 811 for advice on health risks, symptoms and precautions associated with heat. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
